 ObservedPatternintheRadarChart
 · TargetMaturity(greenline):formsanoutercircularbandaroundlevel2.5,indicating
 thattheBASIClevelaimsfora“Repeatable”stateofcontrolimplementationacrossall
 domains.
 · CategoryMaturity(orangeline):remainsnearthe1.0level,indicating“Initial”
 maturity,meaningprocessesexistinsomeformbutareinformalandinconsistently
 applied.
 · DocumentationMaturity(grayline)andImplementationMaturity(blueline)nearly
 overlap,bothhoveringtightlyaround1.0,formingasmallinnercircleatthecenterofthe
 radargraph.
 · ThegraphshowsanotabledepressionintheMaintenance(PR.MA)axis,butall
 categoriesgenerallyremainatorbelowtheInitiallevel(1.0–1.1).
Analytical Interpretation (Strictly Based on Chart Data)
 The CyberFundamentals BASIC radar chart illustrates that the organization’s actual maturity
 remains significantly below the targeted threshold of 2.5 across all functions.
 · Thetarget expectations (green line) represent the required “Repeatable” maturity state
 for entities at BASIC assurance level.
 · However, the measured performance (blue and gray lines) suggests that the
 organization’s cybersecurity posture is still in the “Initial” stage, where procedures are
 mostly undocumented, ad hoc, and dependent on individual effort rather than defined
 processes.
 The radar’s symmetry (almost circular shape at level 1.0) shows consistent underperformance
 across all categories — indicating that the gap between documented controls and operational
 implementation is uniform.
 This means:
 · Policies exist conceptually but lack formalized documentation and procedural
 enforcement.
 · Nocategory exceeds maturity level 1.1, showing minimal variation among IDENTIFY,
 PROTECT, DETECT, RESPOND, and RECOVER functions.
 · Targetmaturity (2.5) is not met in any domain, suggesting foundational work is still
 required to reach a repeatable, process-driven security baseline.
 Interpretive Summary
 The radar chart reflects a low overall cyber maturity profile for BASIC level assessment.
 It conveys that while the organization may understand the required cybersecurity functions
 conceptually, its actual execution and documentation remain at the Initial stage (level 1).
 Visually, the chart shows:
 · TheTarget (green) ring at level 2.5 forming an external perimeter.
 · TheDocumentation (gray) and Implementation (blue) lines overlapping near the
 center at level 1.0, representing early maturity.
 This visual and numeric pattern indicates a uniform capability gap across all domains — a
 typical profile for organizations at the start of their CyberFundamentals Framework compliance
 journey.
